		<font size="1" face="Verdana">posted 2/24/2004 8:06:31 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;

		
		<a href="US_Show.asp?id=32931">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/profile.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to See the Profile for Nosferatu" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="mailto:nosferatu@everlore.com" target="_new">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/email.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to Email Nosferatu" width="24" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MSG_MailBox.asp?mode=new&amp;sendto=Nosferatu">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/privatemsg.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to Message Nosferatu" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=67&FN=Paladin&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=2129462&TN=agro+method&CAT=Classes&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=2129919&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">I'm not a fan of Flash of Light...unless you are with an experienced team that definately knows what they are doing.  BUT, if that's the case you shouldn't need it.</P><P>First of all, understand that keeping aggro isn't just your duty but the whole group's responsibility.</P><P>That being said, you're going overboard.</P><P>Frankly, I keep 3 stuns loaded - Cease, Stun, and Force of Akera (the level 52 stun).  Even if a stun is resisted, it garners aggro.  Cease costs very little mana and casts fairly quickly.  Stun is better than Desist comparing mana cost to effectiveness of the stun itself.  Force of Akera is fast casting, and lands on mobs up to level 61 (I think, might be 60 or 62...I can never remember - but I doubt it's 62, most likely 60).</P><P>FoA is your primary stun when you get up to 55-61.  It's the one that's more guaranteed to land to interrupt.  But use the other two to get aggro or even pull (I use Cease as my pull spell all the time).</P><P>I usually pull with Cease, and run back to camp.  When the mob arrives, I then hit them with FoA - it keeps them stunned for approx 4 secs (IIRC).  By that time, the slower should be casting their slow.  Just this amount of hate is usually enough to keep the mob from aggroing the slower.  But, I usually hit taunt the second I see the slow spell message land.</P><P>By this time, Cease has already refreshed...I hit it again for good measure, as it never hurts to have too much aggro.  This could be considered overboard as well, but the mana usage is negligible.</P><P>I don't even touch disarm anymore.  It's worthless.  I haven't seen a success in ages, and the hate garnered is little.</P><P>I think that answers your question.  I rarely need to do more than that.  I will hit taunt whenever I see a huge critical DD land, just in case.  If using 1h/shield, try to time a bash just after a huge heal/DD/etc (any possible aggro-stealing spell).  That way they are bashed for a sec so you can then taunt/stun.<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
